<div id="Thmexercise1" class="ltx_theorem ltx_theorem_exercise">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_title_theorem"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_theorem"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Exercise 1</span></span> (Markov Chain Existence).</h6>
<div id="Thmexercise1.p1" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p">Let <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="p(x,y)=\kappa(x,\{y\})" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>κ</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></math> be a discrete probability kernel on
<math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m2" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\mathbb{R}^{d}" display="inline"><msup><mi>ℝ</mi><mi>d</mi></msup></math>, <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m3" class="ltx_Math" alttext="p_{0}" display="inline"><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math> a discrete probability distribution. Prove that there
exists a stochastic process <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m4" class="ltx_Math" alttext="X_{n}" display="inline"><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>, such that</p>
<ol id="S0.I1" class="ltx_enumerate">
<li id="S0.I1.i1" class="ltx_item" style="list-style-type:none;"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">1.</span> 
<div id="S0.I1.i1.p1" class="ltx_para ltx_noindent">
<p class="ltx_p"><math id="S0.I1.i1.p1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\mathbb{P}(X_{n}=y\,|\,X_{n-1}=x)=p(x,y)" display="inline"><mrow><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mpadded width="+1.7pt"><mi>y</mi></mpadded><mo rspace="4.2pt" stretchy="false">|</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math> and <math id="S0.I1.i1.p1.m2" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\mathbb{P}(X_{0}=x)=p_{0}(x)" display="inline"><mrow><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></p>
</div></li>
<li id="S0.I1.i2" class="ltx_item" style="list-style-type:none;"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">2.</span> 
<div id="S0.I1.i2.p1" class="ltx_para ltx_noindent">
<p class="ltx_p"><math id="S0.I1.i2.p1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="X_{n}" display="inline"><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> is a Markov Chain, i.e.</p>
<table id="S0.EGx1" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex1"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
<td class="ltx_td ltx_align_right ltx_eqn_cell"><math id="S0.Ex1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\displaystyle\mathbb{P}(X_{n+1}=x_{n+1}\,|\,X_{n}=x_{n},\dots,X_{0}=x_{0})=%&#10;\mathbb{P}(X_{n+1}=x_{n+1}\,|\,X_{n}=x_{n})." display="inline"><mrow><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mpadded width="+1.7pt"><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mpadded><mo rspace="4.2pt" stretchy="false">|</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mpadded width="+1.7pt"><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mpadded><mo rspace="4.2pt" stretchy="false">|</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
</div></li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="Thmhintx1" class="ltx_theorem ltx_theorem_hint">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_title_theorem"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_theorem"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Hint</span></span>.</h6>
<div id="Thmhintx1.p1" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Consider</span></p>
<table id="S0.EGx2" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex2"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
<td class="ltx_td ltx_align_right ltx_eqn_cell"><math id="S0.Ex2.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\displaystyle\mathbb{P}_{X_{0},\dots,X_{n+1}}(A_{0},\dots,A_{n+1}):=\sum_{x_{0%&#10;}\in A_{0}}\dots\sum_{x_{n}\in A_{n}}\kappa(x_{n},A_{n+1})p(x_{n-1},x_{n})%&#10;\dots p(x_{0},x_{1})p_{0}(x_{0})." display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>:=</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle="true"><munder><mo largeop="true" movablelimits="false" symmetric="true">∑</mo><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></munder></mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle="true"><munder><mo largeop="true" movablelimits="false" symmetric="true">∑</mo><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></munder></mstyle><mrow><mi>κ</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
<p class="ltx_p"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_italic">and prove that <math id="Thmhintx1.p1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\mathbb{P}_{X_{0},\dots,X_{n+1}}(A_{0},\dots,A_{n},\mathbb{R}^{d})=\mathbb{P}_%&#10;{X_{0},\dots,X_{n}}(A_{0},\dots,A_{n})" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">P</mi><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn mathvariant="normal">0</mn></msub><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">+</mo><mn mathvariant="normal">1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></msub><mo mathvariant="italic">⁢</mo><mrow><mo mathvariant="normal" stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn mathvariant="normal">0</mn></msub><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi><mi>d</mi></msup><mo mathvariant="normal" stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo mathvariant="normal">=</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">P</mi><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn mathvariant="normal">0</mn></msub><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></msub><mo mathvariant="italic">⁢</mo><mrow><mo mathvariant="normal" stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn mathvariant="normal">0</mn></msub><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">,</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant="normal" stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></math>. Then construct a consistent
family of distributions.</span></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="ltx_proof">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_font_italic ltx_title_proof">Solution.</h6>
<div id="Thmexercise1.p2" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p">We want to define a set of consistent probability measures and then apply
Kolmogorov’s extension theorem. We define</p>
<table id="S0.EGx3" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex3"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
<td class="ltx_td ltx_align_right ltx_eqn_cell"><math id="S0.Ex3.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\displaystyle\mathbb{P}_{\{0,\dots,n+1\}}(A_{0}\times\dots\times A_{n+1}):=%&#10;\sum_{x_{0}\in A_{0}}\dots\sum_{x_{n}\in A_{n}}\kappa(x_{n},A_{n+1})p(x_{n-1},%&#10;x_{n})\dots p(x_{0},x_{1})p_{0}(x_{0})." display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">⋯</mi><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>:=</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle="true"><munder><mo largeop="true" movablelimits="false" symmetric="true">∑</mo><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></munder></mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mstyle displaystyle="true"><munder><mo largeop="true" movablelimits="false" symmetric="true">∑</mo><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></munder></mstyle><mrow><mi>κ</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><msub><mi>p</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
<p class="ltx_p">and for any <math id="Thmexercise1.p2.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="J=\{k_{1},\dots,k_{n}\}" display="inline"><mrow><mi>J</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><msub><mi>k</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow></mrow></math> where w.l.o.g. <math id="Thmexercise1.p2.m2" class="ltx_Math" alttext="k_{1}\leq\dots\leq k_{n}" display="inline"><mrow><msub><mi>k</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>≤</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">⋯</mi><mo>≤</mo><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></math>, we define</p>
<table id="S0.EGx4" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex4"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
