<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
<p class="ltx_p">To prove this family is consistent, as we are infilling anyway, we only
need to prove that we can chop of things at the end, i.e.</p>
<table id="S0.EGx5" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex5"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
<td class="ltx_td ltx_align_right ltx_eqn_cell"><math id="S0.Ex5.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\displaystyle\mathbb{P}_{\{0,\dots,n+1\}}(A_{0}\times\dots\times A_{n}\times%&#10;\mathbb{R}^{d})=\mathbb{P}_{\{0,\dots,n\}}(A_{0}\times\dots\times A_{n})." display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">⋯</mi><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>ℝ</mi><mi>d</mi></msup></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><msub><mi>ℙ</mi><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">…</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow></msub><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">⋯</mi><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td>
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
<p class="ltx_p">But this is true because by definition</p>
<table id="S0.EGx6" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex6"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
